Review analysis of Airbnb listings¶

This notebook serves as a playground to explore the power of word vectors in relation to reviews. The gensim package will be used to create word vectores of Airbnb reviews. The goal is to gain insights into what travelers appreciate and don't appreciate in accommodation choices. A story will be told about the connection between data and the real world.

Preprocessing the data¶

from gensim.models import KeyedVectors
vectors = KeyedVectors.load('word2vec.kv')
In [3]:
my_dict = dict({})
for idx, key in enumerate(vectors.wv.vocab):
    my_dict[key] = vectors.wv[key]

In [5]:
path_list = glob.glob('./entire_homes/reviews/*.csv')
l=[0]*len(path_list)
for i in range(len(path_list)):
    l[i] = pd.read_csv(path_list[i], header=0, index_col=0)

entire_homes = pd.concat(l, ignore_index=True, axis=0)
In [6]:
path_list_private = glob.glob('./private_room_inv/reviews/*.csv')
l=[0]*len(path_list_private)

    l[i] = pd.read_csv(path_list_private[i], header=0, index_col=0)

private_rooms = pd.concat(l, ignore_index=True, axis=0)

In [12]:
def feature_extract(row):

    comment = [review['comments'] for review in row['reviews']]
    language = [review['language'] for review in row['reviews']]
    submit_date = [review['created_at'] for review in row['reviews']]
    review_id = [review['id'] for review in row['reviews']]
    H_superhost = [review['reviewee']['is_superhost'] for review in row['reviews']]
    rating = [review['rating'] for review in row['reviews']]
    deleted = [review['reviewer']['deleted'] for review in row['reviews']]

    medium = pd.DataFrame(np.array([comment,
                       language,
                       submit_date,
                       review_id,
                       H_superhost,
                       rating,
                       deleted])).T

    medium.columns = (['comment','language','date','review_id','H_superhost','rating','deleted'])
    return medium

Prepare reviews comments for language processing¶

In [22]:
import nltk
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
from nltk.stem import WordNetLemmatizer
In [23]:
def review_to_wordlist(raw_review, remove_stopwords=False, lemmatize=True):

    #remove punctuation.
    letters_only = re.sub("[^a-zA-Z]", " ", raw_review)

    #lower case and split.
    words = letters_only.lower().split()

    #remove stopwords if wanted.
    if remove_stopwords:
        stops = set(stopwords.words("english"))
        words = [w for w in words if not w in stops]

    #lemmatize words for better model quality.
    if lemmatize:
        lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
        words = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word, pos='v') for word in words]

    return words
In [24]:
tokenizer = nltk.data.load("tokenizers/punkt/english.pickle")
def review_to_sentence(review, remove_stopwords=False):

    #review to sentence
    raw_sentences = tokenizer.tokenize(review.strip())

    #loop over sentences
    sentences= []
    for raw_sentence in raw_sentences:
        if len(raw_sentence)>0:
            sentences.append(review_to_wordlist(raw_sentence, remove_stopwords=False))

    return sentences

We can now select all english reviews, convert them in to sentences, which will then turned into word vectors.

Bigram/Trigram detector¶

We can introduce to our model a detector for common phrases end expressions, that learns 'la' and 'rambla' to be understood as one entity - 'la rambla'. This way, the model performance could increase and gain more insights about the reviews. The Phrases models from gensim will be used for this.

In [31]:
%%time
from gensim.models import Word2Vec, Phrases
bigram = Phrases(sentences)
trigram = Phrases(bigram[sentences])

CPU times: user 3min 23s, sys: 2.04 s, total: 3min 26s
Wall time: 3min 27s

model_bigram.init_sims(replace=True)

In [43]:
from sklearn.decomposition import IncrementalPCA    # inital reduction
from sklearn.manifold import TSNE                   # final reduction

def reduce_dimensions(model):
    num_dimensions = 2  # final num dimensions (2D, 3D, etc)

    vectors = [] # positions in vector space
    labels = [] # keep track of words to label our data again later
    for word in model.wv.vocab:
        vectors.append(model.wv[word])
        labels.append(word)

    # convert both lists into numpy vectors for reduction
    vectors = np.asarray(vectors)
    labels = np.asarray(labels)

    # reduce first with PCA
    pca = IncrementalPCA(n_components=38)
    vectors = pca.fit_transform(vectors)

    # reduce using t-SNE
    vectors = np.asarray(vectors)
    tsne = TSNE(n_components=num_dimensions, random_state=0)
    vectors = tsne.fit_transform(vectors)

    x_vals = [v[0] for v in vectors]
    y_vals = [v[1] for v in vectors]
    return x_vals, y_vals, labels


x_vals, y_vals, labels = reduce_dimensions(model_bigram)

def plot_with_matplotlib(x_vals, y_vals, labels):
    import random

    random.seed(42)

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 12))
    plt.scatter(x_vals, y_vals, s=2)

    #
    # Label randomly subsampled 25 data points
    #
    indices = list(range(len(labels)))
    selected_indices = random.sample(indices, 200)
    for i in selected_indices:
        plt.annotate(labels[i], (x_vals[i], y_vals[i]))

#create dict of coordinates for easy access.
coor_dict = dict(zip(labels,zip(x_vals, y_vals)))
In [49]:
def cloud_params(model, name):

    #Getting the coordinates of each similar word and the corresponding labels
    similars = model.wv.most_similar(name)
    similar_names = [item[0] for item in similars]
    cloud_coors = np.asarray([coor_dict[item] for item in similar_names])
    cloud_labels = similar_names

    return cloud_coors, cloud_labels
In [50]:
def plot_cloud(model, name):

    coors , labels = cloud_params(model, name)

    #parsing coors into list.
    x_pos = [item[0] for item in coors]
    y_pos = [item[1] for item in coors]

    #Setting the plot.
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
    plt.scatter(x_pos, y_pos)

    #Label the data points.
    for i in range(len(labels)):
        plt.annotate(labels[i], (x_pos[i]+0.02, y_pos[i])) #0.02 marks light offset.

In [58]:
def sky_plot(model, name_list):

    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
    for name in name_list:
        cloud_coors, cloud_labels = cloud_params(model, name)

        x_pos = [item[0] for item in cloud_coors]
        y_pos = [item[1] for item in cloud_coors]

        plt.scatter(x_pos, y_pos)

        for i in range(len(cloud_labels)):
            plt.annotate(cloud_labels[i], (x_pos[i], y_pos[i]))
In [59]:
sky_plot(model_bigram,['hospitality', 'cozy', 'friendly', 'value'])
In [60]:
def cloud_to_csv(name, path):

    #Create numpy array including labels and coors.
    cloud_coors, cloud_labels = cloud_params(model_bigram, name)
    word_array = np.concatenate([np.asarray(cloud_labels).reshape(-1,1),cloud_coors], axis=1)

    #Create numpy array of center word 'name'.
    center_word = np.concatenate([np.asarray((name)).reshape(-1,1),
                                  np.asarray(coor_dict[name]).reshape(1,-1)],
                                  axis=1)

    #Concat arrays and create dataframe.   
    hosp_df = pd.DataFrame(np.concatenate([word_array, center_word]))

    #Save to CSV.
    hosp_df.to_csv(path, header=False)
    print(f'Cloud saved to {path}')

Sentiment analysis.¶

Bag of Clusters¶

Goal is to cluster the words and execute a sentiment analysis with the review scores. Indentified should be the most important clusters to classify a review with a forest classifier.

In [ ]:
model_result_list = []
In [ ]:
%%time
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
word_vectors = model_bigram.wv.vectors
num_clusters = 800 #int(model_bigram.wv.vectors.shape[0]/5)

# Initalize a k-means object and use it to extract centroids
kmeans_clustering = KMeans(n_clusters = num_clusters)
idx = kmeans_clustering.fit_predict( word_vectors )

word_centroid_map = dict(zip(list(model_bigram.wv.vocab.keys()), idx ))
In [ ]:
word_centroid_map
In [ ]:
# For the first 10 clusters
for cluster in range(0,100):
    #
    # Print the cluster number  
    print ("\nCluster %d" % cluster)
    #
    # Find all of the words for that cluster number, and print them out
    words = []
    for i in range(0,len(word_centroid_map)):
        if( list(word_centroid_map.values())[i] == cluster ):
            words.append(list(word_centroid_map.keys())[i])
    print (words)

#Prepare the train data
df = medium[medium.language == 'en'].copy()

def create_bag_of_centroids( wordlist, word_centroid_map ):
    #
    # The number of clusters is equal to the highest cluster index
    # in the word / centroid map
    num_centroids = max( word_centroid_map.values() ) + 1
    #
    # Pre-allocate the bag of centroids vector (for speed)
    bag_of_centroids = np.zeros( num_centroids, dtype="float32" )
    #
    # Loop over the words in the review. If the word is in the vocabulary,
    # find which cluster it belongs to, and increment that cluster count 
    # by one
    for word in wordlist:
        if word in word_centroid_map:
            index = word_centroid_map[word]
            bag_of_centroids[index] += 1
    #
    # Return the "bag of centroids"
    return bag_of_centroids

def prec_vs_recall(precision, recall,thresholds):
    plt.plot(thresholds, precision[:-1], 'b--', label='Precision')
    plt.plot(thresholds, recall[:-1], 'g-', label='Recall')
    plt.xlabel('Threshold')
    plt.legend(loc='upper left')
    plt.ylim([0,1])

Vector Averaging¶

In [ ]:
def makeFeatureVec(words, model, num_features):
    # Function to average all of the word vectors in a given
    # paragraph
    #
    # Pre-initialize an empty numpy array (for speed)
    featureVec = np.zeros((num_features,),dtype="float32")
    #
    nwords = 0.
    # 
    # Index2word is a list that contains the names of the words in 
    # the model's vocabulary. Convert it to a set, for speed 
    index2word_set = set(model.wv.index2word)
    #
    # Loop over each word in the review and, if it is in the model's
    # vocaublary, add its feature vector to the total
    for word in words:
        if word in index2word_set:
            nwords = nwords + 1.
            featureVec = np.add(featureVec,model.wv[word])
    # 
    # Divide the result by the number of words to get the average
    featureVec = np.divide(featureVec,nwords)
    return featureVec


def getAvgFeatureVecs(reviews, model, num_features):
    # Given a set of reviews (each one a list of words), calculate 
    # the average feature vector for each one and return a 2D numpy array 
    # 
    # Initialize a counter
    counter = 0
    # 
    # Preallocate a 2D numpy array, for speed
    reviewFeatureVecs = np.zeros((len(reviews),num_features),dtype="float32")
    # 
    # Loop through the reviews
    for review in reviews:

       # Print a status message every 1000th review
       if counter%1000 == 0:

           print(f"Review {counter} of {len(reviews)}")
       #
       # Call the function (defined above) that makes average feature vectors
       reviewFeatureVecs[counter] = makeFeatureVec(review, model, \
           num_features)
       #
       # Increment the counter
       counter = counter + 1
    return reviewFeatureVecs
